portsIn.value: I have been chasing that vibration ever since. Sometimes it hides in the warmth of wood, in the echo of a marimba bar that still resonates after the mallet has left it. Sometimes it hides in silence in that mysterious, weightless pause where the music seems to hold its breath and wait for something unnamed. I often wonder what it means to belong to sound. My journey has taken me from the narrow streets of Onda to the classrooms of Valencia, from the vastness of Germanys grey skies to the strange intimacy of a dark theater before the lights come up. Yet everywhere I go, I carry the same question: what is it that music really says, when it stops trying to impress and begins to confess? Playing percussion taught me to think with my hands, to listen not only outward but inward. The vibraphone, especially, feels like an instrument of memory each note fades, yet leaves a trace, like breath on glass. Perhaps thats what draws me to theater: the way it allows music to dissolve into human gesture, into fragility, into something transient and true. When I compose for the stage, I no longer think of melody or harmony first. I think of presence of a pulse beneath words, of the secret rhythm of an actors inhale. The music becomes a mirror, sometimes reflecting, sometimes contradicting, always listening. There are days when I miss the certainty of scores and competitions, the illusion that art can be measured. But more and more, I find beauty in what escapes control in the accidental, the improvised, the imperfect. The mallet misses the center of the bar, and suddenly, a new color appears. Maybe thats where truth hides: in the deviation, in the human tremor that no technique can erase. Ive come to believe that to make music is to stand between sound and silence, to accept that we are both the resonance and the fading echo. Every performance, every note, is an act of disappearance and yet, somehow, in disappearing, it leaves a trace of who we are.
